Given an integer n. You need to generate all the binary strings of n characters representing bits.

Note: Return the strings in  ascending order.

Examples:

Input: n = 2
Output: [00, 01, 10, 11]
Explanation: As each position can be either 0 or 1, the total possible combinations are 4.
Input: n = 3
Output: [000, 001, 010, 011, 100, 101, 110, 111]
Explanation: As each position can be either 0 or 1, the total possible combinations are 8.
=========================================

At every position:You have 2 choices.
Put '0' 
Put '1'
So the recursion forms a binary tree.

Visual Animation (Recursion Tree)
Start with empty string:
""
Level 1 (Position 0)
          ""
         /    \
       "0"    "1"
Level 2 (Position 1)
            ""
         /        \
       "0"        "1"
      /   \       /   \
   "00"  "01"  "10"  "11"
Level 3 (Position 2)
                ""
        /                    \
      "0"                    "1"
     /     \               /       \
   "00"   "01"           "10"      "11"
   /  \     /  \         /   \      /   \
000   001  010   011      100    101    110     111

üéâ When length becomes 3 ‚Üí we print.

What Is Happening Internally (Stack Animation)

Think in terms of:
Add ‚Üí Add ‚Üí Add ‚Üí Print ‚Üí Remove ‚Üí Add ‚Üí Print ‚Üí Remove ‚Üí Remove...

Example flow:
""  
"0"
"00"
"000"  ‚úî print
"00"
"001"  ‚úî print
"0"
"01"
"010" ‚úî
...

Backtracking = removing last character after returning.

=========

class Solution {
    public ArrayList<String> binstr(int n) {
        ArrayList<String> ansList=new ArrayList<>();
        helper(ansList,"",n);
        return ansList;
    }
    
    public void helper(ArrayList<String> list,String current,int n)
    {
        if(current.length()==n)
        {
            list.add(current);
            return;
        }
        //left recursive call
        helper(list,current+"0",n);
        helper(list,current+"1",n);
    }
}


or

public class BinaryStrings {
    public static void generate(String current, int n) {
        // Base case
        if (current.length() == n) {
            System.out.println(current);
            return;
        }
        // Choose '0'
        generate(current + "0", n);
        // Choose '1'
        generate(current + "1", n);
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        int n = 3;
        generate("", n);
    }
}


Interview Explanation Version
If interviewer asks how it works, say:
"At each position, I have two choices: append '0' or '1'.
I recursively build the string.
When its length becomes n, I print it.
Since every position has 2 choices, total combinations are 2‚Åø."

‚è± Complexity
Time: O(2‚Åø)
Space (recursion stack): O(n)
